Clubs may spend huge amounts on the purchase of players, but on the other hand they must demonstrate legal sources of income, which allows them to cover the overhead costs of football-related business activities.
The FFP introduced Michel Platini to the chair of the director of UEFA in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that were in debt in pursuit of new reinforcements ultimately cheated and risked bankruptcy if banks or owners refused to secure them.
In 2011, FFP's rules redirected its attention from club debt to monitoring their losses.
This change meant that the business model used by Roman Abramovich and Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with potential and to spend the aggregate sums on players to build a global brand - was suddenly not so advantageous.
