The first wave of the highest FFP sanctions hit PSG in 2014 along with Manchester City, owned by Abu Dhabi.
PSG received a fine of EUR 60 million ($82 million) - which was later reduced to EUR 20 million - and a command to reduce the Champions League team to 21 players in 2014-2015, instead of 25 players.
UEFA is careful of teams that can try to circumvent financial regulators by increasing their income through companies associated with club owners.
Therefore, although the Qatarian company sponsors PSG as soon as financing exceeds the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit the billing of the amount.
A similar measure was taken by UEFA in 2014 after deciding that the amount of funding provided by the Qatar Tourism Authority to the PSG team was too high.
