NHS will prescribe a controversial HIV drug for 10,000 patients
Since September, patients will receive access to "transformative' treatment for HIV prevention by decision of the Supreme Court on funding NHS.
The English National Health Service (NSH) announced that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PREP) pill, which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through medical services to approximately 10,000 patients within a three-year trial period.
The NSH agreed to finance the probationary period after the appeal court supported the Supreme Court's decision last year, stating that the NHS had funds to pay the Prep despite the declaration that the drug should be financed by local authorities.
The decision announced on Thursday was taken by NHS England from the mouth of CEO Simon Stevens as "a major intervention', while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as "the decisive moment'.
Clinics of sexual health in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start receiving patients. Other clinics will join in October and by April 2018 full implementation will take place throughout England.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PREP) is an HIV drug used before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PREP significantly reduces the risk of transmission of HIV among patients at risk.
Prep before sex means that there are enough specific medicines in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These medicines can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Tested patients include homosexual or bisexual men, transsexual people, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics shall identify eligible participants who sign consent to participate in testing, including men, women, transsexuals and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with the GP in the UK can also apply in their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program will come to taxpayers at £10 million and NHS England signed this week's drug distribution contract after obtaining an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to collect clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PREP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: "This important intervention should complement and fully burden ever-increasing and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than 30 years of trying to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, Executive Director of NAT (National Aids Trust), said: "We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PREP is administered correctly and patients are at risk, it will offer the possibility of changing the English HIV epidemic.
Since September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection with a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will improve the quality of many lives.
We are pleased to accept this statement.'
Ian Green, CEO of Terrence Higgins Trust, said: "The number one priority must be the rapid deployment of tests across the country; we must ensure its availability to every patient.
We now have a PrEP trial drug available and are on the right track to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection.'
Shadow Minister Sharon Hodgson said: "The beginning of the Prep trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Follow-up tests will bring us one step closer to full understanding of Prep's benefits.
It is now important that we start the tests as soon as possible across the country to protect those exposed to HIV and thus jointly end the spread of HIV in society.'
Life on high feet: Mezzanine and smart design have turned this small apartment into a spacious home at Earls Court
Joanne Leigh, a former banker with a passion for real estate, traded a big house in Knightsbridge in 2014 for an apartment at Earls Cour.
