"I lived with my ex-husband earlier in a much bigger house in Knightsbridge," Joanne said.
"I was looking for something at a more reasonable price.
I ran into this apartment at Earls Court, and it was the same height of the ceiling.
I fell in love with him immediately, and on the same day I nodded to him."
Since then, the apartment with a size of 1000 square meters has been completely renovated.
One-room apartment with complicated layout - to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen - Joanne wanted to add storage space and mezzanine to use the high ceiling.
"I longed for high ceilings, big windows and lots of light.
Those were my demands," she said.
For this purpose, she employed Erfan Azadi from the design studio Duck & Shed, based in Notting Hill, and used an almost four-metre ceiling to create a home that was not just a project, but also a place to live.
The ceiling did not reach enough height to accommodate two gaps - the challenge for architects was to create a mezzanine that could be walked upright.
Erfan had to engage his creative thinking.
"The steel structure is quite complicated," he explained.
"We had to organize both spaces so that we could walk upright.
It was not only about building a simple platform but at the same time bending the steel structure so that at the right height above and below the ceiling."
This arrangement enabled Erfan to construct two full rooms on himself - and at the same time add to the drama.
The mezzanine overlooks the beautiful living room of the old copper window frames in Retrouvius design.
Mirror furniture in gold color, silver lines and retro chandelier Serge Mouille creates a unique style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in drama, space and lighting.
The short corridor is equipped with mirrors on both sides and looks longer.
The mirror bar in the kitchen looks like a window to the next room.
At the entrance door there are storage spaces equipped with mirrors to store cutlery and jars.
The advantage of the living room, which gives the whole apartment an impression of a significantly larger space, is the possibility to separate it from the kitchen if it is not used.
The tilting kitchens are nothing new.
What is unique about this solution, however, is the folding door.
"We had to solve the technical side," Erfan says about reinforced veneered doors.
"The door is equipped with counterweights to move away very easily."
Thanks to the smart use of space and storage space, Joanne has gained another 16 square meters, second room and better overall layout of the apartment.
"When it comes down to it, what you're selling is the living space - or appreciation of your property," Erfan said.
"The real estate broker essentially calculates its price on the basis of the residential area when entering the apartment."
In this case, it was possible to increase the living space while maintaining quality materials that lend space a luxurious look.
"The material is very important because you touch it and create an emotional bond with your home," Erfan added.
"You won't love power lines in the walls.
Yes, they are important, but your hearts will not gain."
As it turns out, quality design and an increase in living space can turn an ordinary apartment into an exceptional work.
And like Joanne, eventually you can decide to stay.
