A Becoming Resemblance: The artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of one of New York's New York's rooms, the Fridman Gallery is placed with several faces of different skin shades - white, black and dark - hanging from the ceiling on the wires, each of them as if the previous one had fallen out of the eye.
All 30 portraits were made by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from oral and hair swabs sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where a former analyst serves a 35-year sentence for unauthorized disclosure of secret cablegrams on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which started on 2 August, bears the name A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her experience with technology, computer science and art, and Manning - a transsexual and pioneering dissident whose sentence was reduced by Obama three days before he left the US President.
By algorithmic analysis of Manning's DNA and by using 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a slim, if not intellectual commentary on DNA yield - as well as the many ways in which DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, who was born as Bradley Edward Manning, has spoken since her youth about being considered a woman. She was convicted in 2013 on the basis of 20 charges, including the violation of six spy laws, computer fraud, and theft.
All her photos were held by the prison staff, and only one black and white photograph of a lower quality leaked to the public, to which Manning, visibly concerned, sits in the driver's seat in a platinum blond wig, with which she is now associated.
In 2015, there were still positive responses to the 2012 Dewey-Hagborg project Stranger Visions.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic items - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create a picture of possible forms of these people.
And it was at this time that she received an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They were going to interview Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to complete the article with a portrait," Dewey-Hagborg explained on the occasion of the opening of the new exhibition.
Visits and photos were not allowed, so they asked Chelsea if she was interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends within two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic book called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, who presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were pardoned and could attend the exhibition in person.
Indeed, President Obama asked for Manning's release a few days after the release of the comic book, which was a welcome change after several unbearable years spent in a military prison in Kansas.
It is indeed interesting that the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is waging a war with people who are seeking to publish government information and transgender soldiers while trying to find new ways to inspire hatred by their tweets in areas that he should support.
In response to a question about this particular timing, Dewey-Hagborg said that "everything happens for a reason"
Under the statement of the artist on one of the walls of the gallery, Manning calls with her huge signature (the letter "i" in her last name is flown by the heart) after the end of "self-actionary factionism based on sex, race, sexuality and culture."
On the opposite side are sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - Centipede letters C, G and A recorded in pencil.
By listing 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the sophisticated scientific dictionary of the artist) Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biological, we all are.
"I hope that people will get away with this, that our genome doesn't matter who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it their way," Dewey-Hagborg said.
"DNA tells many different stories, this is 30 of them."
The last specimen of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is the only page from the above-mentioned graphic novel.
He's showing Manning as King Kong emerges from United States Disciplinary Barracks with a megaphone in his hand.
"As soon as they stop you from speaking, they win," it says.
"Never be silenced."
"It is a direct transcript of one of the letters," said the Philadelphia artist.
"When I think about it, I get goose bumps."
Manning has not yet personally visited the exhibition - which was predicted in a comic book - but when she does, she will be welcomed in the center of the room with her masks, her own genome portraits, sorted as a crowd of Protestants.
This was also the purpose of the exhibition, including the almost 160 cm tall statue of Maning, on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded in pencil.
"In the past they were placed on the walls, but this time I wanted them to glow the feeling of the crowd," Dewey-Hagborg said about the portraits.
"I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement that takes the form of Chelsea and frees her."
