Vice-President of the Russian Government Vitaly Mutko said that it will not take long to implement the remaining criteria of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) and the re-established Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA).
"A part of the criteria of the new plan has been completed and RUSADA has already acquired the right to plan and test in cooperation with the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
In view of this, the WADA plan was updated," Mutko said on Thursday.
The Vice-President commented on the second part of the WADA's compliance plan - which describes the criteria for the renewal of the RUSADA - which was recently published on the organisation's website.
According to Mutka, the code does not contain anything that Russia should be concerned about.
"Everything has been announced and everything will also be implemented.
The results will be available to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA shortly," he added.
However, one of the above criteria calls for the public announcement of the results of the WADA investigation, which Richard McLaren investigated, of the alleged sponsoring of doping by the government of Russian athletes.
On this subject, Mutko said: "We are conducting an investigation because our anti-doping system clearly failed.
All measures have been taken.
But there were no state programs in our country, and we cannot confess to something that never existed."
Mutka's words were confirmed by Vitaly Smirnov, director of the Russian Independent Public Anti-Doping Commission.
In an interview for Russian RSport Smirnov admitted the problems of Russian anti-doping agents, but he added: "On many occasions we said that the report contains controversial positions and regulations.
No one plans to accept the report without reservation," Smirnov concluded.
WADA suspected RUSADA of taking doping controls within Russia in November 2015 immediately before the doping scandal.
However, the organisation authorised planning and unification of testing under the supervision of international experts and the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD) this June.
Following a visit to Moscow's headquarters in July, General Manager WADA Olivier Niggle stated that RUSADA is "on the right track" to renew its validity.
