Startups that will help your company not become another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the level of satisfaction of the employees of her e-commerce startup, but she didn't find the appropriate survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, useless, or even misleading.
And despite promising the anonymity of the survey, some employees expressed their distrust of the entire process.
"I was looking for consistency and objectivity," said Errett, owner of the e-commerce company, Madison Reed, based in San Francisco, who employs 75 people.
So she asked for help from the outside.
New human resources startups are constantly appearing on the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with a specific intention of measuring employees' obligations, startups allow companies to vote quickly, target specific teams and demographic groups, and offer complete anonymity of employees and a hotline for complaints, and in some cases also allow informants to bypass their superiors and contact the director directly.
"There are tools like Diet and Fitbit on the market that monitor your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of the Glint Startup based in Reedwood City.
Errett said that Glint has given her three years of greater awareness of what her employees think and feel.
In addition to quick surveys and specific team voting, Glint offers a company temperature map and a timely overview of groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of low-rated managers - allowing users to work on the correction.
Companies are beginning to realize that it is necessary to take care of the culture of the working environment - in case they become another Uber - which is torn up in scandals after a former employee posted on his blog a contribution describing the corporate environment and harassment of employees who dare to speak openly.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the Let's Talk Payments website, which deals with technical and financial progress, the value of the global sector of control, regulation and compliance may exceed $11.8 billion by 2020.
Startup Convert from Denver, Colorado, which helps companies to prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small increase in interest and activity at the beginning of the year, just before Uber scandals.
Nearly 600 of Convercent's clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently under his wings he also accepted Uber.
Like Glint, Convert allows companies to send customizable "flash" surveys, collect confidential information in real time and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
Where the Director-General is involved, complaints shall be sent directly to the Management Board.
"The court of public opinion has authorized regulators," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of the Convercent Startup.
If the company is convicted of mistreatment of its employees or non-ethical behaviour - and if the regulators do not intervene - it can face costly consequences as a result of customer boycott, employee exhaustion or legal proceedings, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant network, which employs over 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convert for more than a year to raise employees' awareness of corporate policies and procedures and ensure an easy way to contact corporate leadership.
Previously, if the employee wanted to report any problem, he had to track down a phone number or e-mail to the company management, officially file a complaint and hope for a successful resolution.
It was often a deterrent and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, Deputy General Ruby Tuesday, according to which there was previously no reliable way to monitor employee complaints.
Now that the company is using Convert, quick detection and resolution of problems that have previously never reached managers sitting in offices is ensured, miles away, from a real solution to complaints - such as discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
"It is close to the holistic, overall view of employees' experience," said Vitrano, who manages Ruby Tuesday's risk management group.
"At the same time, we protect shareholders from lawsuits by employees."
Companies stopped taking the ethics, values and employee participation lightly in 2002 after Arthur Andersen's accounting firm collapsed after Enron's fall on the abuse of employees' ethical rights, Quinlan said.
But only when "the social media shined on the whole thing " did society begin to realize that they could not simply hide their skeletons in the closet in the online world.
"Before people started using technology to monitor the ethics of technology, they relied on faith," Quinlan said.
Both Glint and Convert offer their software in the form of a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It is a business model and an opportunity approved by courageous capital investors who have supported both start-ups.
Convercent collected total $10 million from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital as part of his February campaign, and finally took the capital of $47 million.
Glint won $10 million from the Bessemer Venture Partners in November and won $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of companies, culture and risk capital.
The increasing number of researches clearly confirms that today's employees expect more from their workplace than ever.
And in competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, high salaries and interesting projects are not the main advantage.
Employees want to see that they are accepted and appreciated and that they devote their time to a society that seeks a positive mission.
"If people are happy in their work, they perceive that their voice is heard and that their work is rewarding, they strive for the success of society," said Nina McQueen, Vice President of Global Benefits and Employee Benefits of LinkedIn, who uses both Convert and Glint.
Investors make money if companies and companies thrive if their employees are satisfied.
And when an analytical tool appears on the market to ensure the involvement and commitment of employees to the company, it is no wonder that there are many investors who support this effort.
According to professional culture experts, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is pointless if the company doesn't take the necessary steps.
The fact is that when a company applies for feedback from its employees, there may be major changes.
And if the change doesn't happen quickly - in the worst case scenario at all - it can cause disappointment and disinterest in employees.
"As soon as you ask for 4000 opinions, you must be prepared for 4000 conversations," said Russell Raath, Director of Counseling at Kotter International, who witnessed many companies that relied too much on the data itself.
"Because once things aren't over, the employees start asking themselves, "Did they even hear me?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, then why should it interest me?'""
Thanks to Glint, Madison Reed, who now regularly conducts an employee survey every month, can solve the problem within one day, says Errett.
After gathering feedback from employees who were frustrated by the slow decision-making and quality of communication, Errett was able to reorganize several teams within the company and start training communication to resolve the problem successfully.
Ruby Tuesday acquires a very important view of its employees and hopes to achieve high employment in the long term, which is known for frequent redundancies.
"If you do not seek to create a transparent working environment, employees will not believe you," Vitrano added.
"And once you start losing employees, you lose customers.
And with the customer's tide, the whole company is going to go bankrupt."
