Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can relieve symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
However, the new study suggests the opposite: diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
An incurable disease that affects up to 1.3 million U.S. residents and 300,000 UK patients causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to use meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms. However, researchers at the University of Washington have found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps to create immune cells that support intestinal resistance.
The head of Dr. Marco Colonna's study explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure removal of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
Once the scales are tilted to the side of inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease may occur.
As part of the research, scientists have found the presence of immune cells supporting the tolerance of the body in the stomach of mice with specific bacteria.
This bacteria requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the protein building blocks to create cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We found a connection between one species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a common part of the intestinal microbioma and the development of cells that promote tolerance of the body.
The more tryptophan mice had in their diet, the more they had these immune cells."
At the same time, he suggested that if it turns out that the same applies to humans, then the combination of L. reuteri bacteria and diet rich in tryptophan would help develop a more tolerated and less inflammatory intestinal environment.
