The White House prop cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
The decision of the White House to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn to celebrate the American manufacturing industry last month was $24,000.
The Green White helicopter Sikorsky VH-3D, also known as Marine One in the presence of the President on board, was the highlight of the July 17 program in the White House, which was a parade of American design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and several senior White House officials have been looking at a product show from all 50 states.
The helicopter from Connecticut was displayed next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift cart from Mississippi.
Military officer of the White House issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, and requested the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn under the "extraordinary" event, reported Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) - units responsible for managing the helicopter.
"I wanted to make sure that you were aware of such a significant event," wrote HMX-1 in an e-mail to his superior, deputy commander of the Navy for aviation the day before the start of the event.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7:00 a.m. on the occasion of a parade scheduled to begin at 3:00 p.m. and will remain in place until the whole place was completely cleared out, scheduled between 18:00 and 21:00 p.m.
The e-mail further stated that if there was a delay on departure from the White House, a replacement crew would be sent for a return flight due to a working time regulation.
The original crew remained on site that evening along with the helicopter and along with them also a unit of security personnel.
The records - which the Time weekly received - did not show if the second crew was finally sent.
The Hatch Act prevents civil servants from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating a possible breach of this Regulation.
"We were wondering if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was okay," the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you've been blocked," wrote the deputy commander.
This show "Made in America" was marked by the White House as an official event and the Hatch Act would therefore not apply to it.
But even official events have political subtexts.
In his participation in the event, the President advocated a health reform that went through the Senate and talked about an attempt to keep government regulations under control.
The use of air vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
The presidents use them to travel.
However, their presence purely for presentation reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after the presidential plane was riding in the background during his first meeting in the Melbourne campaign in Florida. His Twitter account is overwhelmed by complaints about the use of the presidential aircraft by his predecessors.
"The White House is pleased with the show "Made in America', which presented products from all 50 states produced by Americans from American materials," said Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often train landing in the Washington and South Lawn area and rehearse possible arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum precision.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America parade was part of the current crew training, stated the state official.
The helicopter unit on the same day was flying under the "non-president support missions" for the next eleven hours.
The White House said that no additional props were paid out of taxpayers' money.
Sikorsky said that the company was in no way involved in the negotiations on the exposition of a helicopter to South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not retain budget records for presidential flights and the exact cost of the show is, according to the Navy, difficult to determine.
According to the Ministry of Defence, the hourly price for the fiscal year 2017, is the reimbursement of DoD expenses for VH-3D $24,380 per flight hour.
Unit records indicate 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico base in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below that amount.
"It is very misleading to place taxpayers' costs on the basis of estimates for reimbursement of expenditure," Walters said.
"These estimates include staff, maintenance and many other hidden costs that are included in annual costs."
According to the 2015 RAND study, the costs of the DoD do not include personnel costs but include fuel costs, maintenance costs and contractual costs.
The White House's press secretary, Sean Spicer, defended the use of a helicopter for parade purposes.
"The idea of the parade taking place this week is to introduce products manufactured in the USA," Spicer said.
"I am aware that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to the defence of our state and that they provide work for hundreds, if not thousands of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and other military facilities that countless American citizens are involved in making.
This is a fact to be recalled."
It is unclear whether Trump was also looking at the helicopter during his rounds at South Lawn. With certainty can only say that he sat behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back at the White House Trump approached Sikorsky's representative and joked with the media about his own product fleet.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the President, "I own three myself."
